/location></wwevent></wwlong><lecturers><lecturer id="49839" type="V"><firstname>Torsten</firstname><lastname>Möller</lastname></lecturer><lecturer id="30990" type="P"><firstname>Manfred</firstname><lastname>Klaffenböck</lastname></lecturer><lecturer id="90001332" type="VO"><firstname>Lukas</firstname><lastname>Lipp</lastname></lecturer><lecturer id="90001331" type="VO"><firstname>Annalena</firstname><lastname>Ulschmid</lastname></lecturer><lecturer id="90001333" type="VO"><firstname>Michael</firstname><lastname>Wimmer</lastname></lecturer></lecturers><registrations><enroll from="2025-02-10T09:00:00+01:00" to="2025-02-21T09:00:00+01:00"/><disenroll until="2025-03-14T23:59:00+01:00"/></registrations><info><comment xml:lang="de">This course builds upon the fundamental principles covered in Foundations of Computer Graphics (05-2200) and introduces students to advanced topics in computer graphics. This particular course focuses on image synthesis, i.e. the creation of photo-realistic images. Specific topics include:&lt;br&#47;&gt;* review of basics&lt;br&#47;&gt;* advanced ray tracing&lt;br&#47;&gt;* radiometry &#47; photometry&lt;br&#47;&gt;* image pipeline&lt;br&#47;&gt;* reflectance functions&lt;br&#47;&gt;* Monte-Carlo methods&lt;br&#47;&gt;* photon maps&lt;br&#47;&gt;* radiosity&lt;br&#47;&gt;* participating media&lt;p&#47;&gt;Students are enabled to:&lt;br&#47;&gt;* analyse and solve the rendering equation using sophisticated mathematical and statistical methods&lt;br&#47;&gt;* extend a large code base (in C++) and learn how to debug such a system&lt;br&#47;&gt;* analyse and improve rendering algorithms based on efficiency of ray&lt;br&#47;&gt;intersections&lt;br&#47;&gt;* tell apart biased and convergent behaviour of a rendering algorithm&lt;p&#47;&gt;Students gain:&lt;br&#47;&gt;* deep insight into the art and science of physically-based rendering&lt;br&#47;&gt;* an appreciation for applied statistics and applied numerical mathematics&lt;br&#47;&gt;* experience with a production quality rendering system (pbrt)</comment><performance xml:lang="de">4xAssignments: 50%&lt;br&#47;&gt;Final Exam: 50%</performance><literature xml:lang="de">Pharr, Matt; Humphreys, Greg: Physically based rendering : from theory to implementation, Morgan Kaufmann, 2023 (4th edition)</literature><examination xml:lang="de">* applied exercises and tasks&lt;br&#47;&gt;* accomplishing a final project&lt;br&#47;&gt;* in-class presentations&lt;br&#47;&gt;* readings</examination><preconditions xml:lang="de">A mandatory prerequisite for this class is the successful completion of Foundations of Computer Graphics (05-2200).&lt;p&#47;&gt;The grading scale for the course will be:&lt;br&#47;&gt;1: at least 87.5%&lt;br&#47;&gt;2: at least 75.0%&lt;br&#47;&gt;3: at least 60.0%&lt;br&#47;&gt;4: at least 40.0%&lt;p&#47;&gt;A minimum grade of 25% must be earned on each assignment (without considering penalties) in order to pass the course.</preconditions></info></group></groups><offeredby id="8505">SPL 5 - Informatik und Wirtschaftsinformatik</offeredby></course>